{"title_page": "Smederevo Stadium", "text_new": "{{infobox stadium\n| name                = Smederevo Stadium\n| image               = Stadion FK Smederevo.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| caption             = The [[north]] stand features ''[[Despoti]]'' inscription in dedication to [[FK Smederevo 1924|Smederevo's]] fans\n| fullname            = Smederevo Stadium \n| nickname            = '''\u0422\u0432\u0440\u0452\u0430\u0432\u0430 / Tvr\u0111ava'''<br>(Fortress)\n| former_names        = Sartid Stadium\n| location            = [[Smederevo]], {{flag|Serbia}}\n| coordinates         = {{coord|44|39|38.28|N|20|54|6.24|E|}}\n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = 1930 \n| opened              = \n| renovated           = \n| expanded            = 1993-94, 1996, 1998, 1999, 2000\n| closed              =\n| demolished          =\n| owner               = [[FK Smederevo 1924]]\n| operator            = [[FK Smederevo 1924]]\n| surface             = [[grass]]\n| scoreboard          = yes\n| construction_cost   = \n| suites              = \n| architect           = \n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 17,200 (seated)\n| executive_suites    = \n| dimensions          = 105 x 68 m\n| acreage             = \n| tenants             = [[FK Smederevo 1924]]\n}}\n[[File:Severna tribina stadiona u Smederevu.jpg|thumb|right|230px|North stand stadium]]\n'''Smederevo Stadium''' ({{lang-sr|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0424\u041a \u0421\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e}} / Stadion FK Smederevo), known as '''[[Fortress Stadium (disambiguation)|Fortress]]''' ({{lang-sr|\u0422\u0432\u0440\u0452\u0430\u0432\u0430}} / Tvr\u0111ava), is a [[Soccer-specific stadium|football stadium]] in [[Smederevo]], [[Serbia]]. It is currently used mostly for [[Association football|football]] matches and is the home ground of [[FK Smederevo 1924]]. The stadium has a [[seating capacity]] for 17,200 spectators. The stadium was previously known as '''Sartid Stadium''' ({{lang-sr|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0424\u041a \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0434}} / Stadion FK Sartid).\n\n==History==\nThe stadium got its current appearance from its most recent reconstruction in 2000. The venue hosted a [[2009 European Cup]] [[rugby league]] match, when [[Serbia national rugby league team|Serbia]] played [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]].\n\nIn late August 2012, an unidentified virus infected the grass at the stadium and forced [[FK Smederevo]] to play its fixtures outside of the stadium until the grass was changed.<ref>[http://www.sportske.net/vest/domaci-fudbal/nepoznata-bolest-napala-travu-na-stadionu-smedereva-93323.html Nepoznata bolest napala travu na stadionu Smedereva!?] ''www.sportske.net'' {{in lang|sr}}</ref>\n\n==International matches==\n[[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia national football team|FR Yugoslavia national football team]] played here once.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=\"30\" |#\n!width=\"150\"|Date\n!width=\"200\"|Competition\n!width=\"200\" |Opponent\n!width=\"100\"|Score\n!width=\"60\"|Att.\n!width=\"30\" |Ref\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|{{flag_icon|FR Yugoslavia}} '''[[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FR Yugoslavia]]''' (1992\u20132003)\n|-\n|1.||17 April 2002 ||align=\"left\"|[[Friendly match]] ||align=\"left\"|{{fb|LIT}} ||bgcolor=\"#00FF00\"|'''4\u20131 (2\u20131)''' ||15,000 ||<ref>[http://www.reprezentacija.rs/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=140&Itemid=60 SR Jugoslavija - Litvanija] ''www.reprezentacija.rs'' {{in lang|sr}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of football stadiums in Serbia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Football venues in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Multi-purpose stadiums in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Rugby league stadiums in Serbia]]\n[[Category:FK Smederevo]]\n\n\n{{Serbia-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{ infobox stadium\n| name                = Smederevo Stadium\n| image               = Stadion FK Smederevo.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| caption             = The [[north]] stand features ''[[Despoti]]'' inscription in dedication to [[FK Smederevo 1924|Smederevo's]] fans\n| fullname            = Smederevo Stadium \n| nickname            = '''\u0422\u0432\u0440\u0452\u0430\u0432\u0430 / Tvr\u0111ava'''<br>(Fortress)\n| former_names        = Sartid Stadium\n| location            = [[Smederevo]], {{flag|Serbia}}\n| coordinates         = {{coord|44|39|38.28|N|20|54|6.24|E|}}\n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = 1930 \n| opened              = \n| renovated           = \n| expanded            = 1993-94, 1996, 1998, 1999, 2000\n| closed              =\n| demolished          =\n| owner               = [[FK Smederevo 1924]]\n| operator            = [[FK Smederevo 1924]]\n| surface             = [[grass]]\n| scoreboard          = yes\n| construction_cost   = \n| suites              = \n| architect           = \n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 17,200 (seated)\n| executive_suites    = \n| dimensions          = 105 x 68\n| acreage             = \n| tenants             = [[FK Smederevo 1924]]\n}}\n[[File:Severna tribina stadiona u Smederevu.jpg|thumb|right|230px|North stand stadium]]\n'''Smederevo Stadium''' ({{lang-sr|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0424\u041a \u0421\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e}} / Stadion FK Smederevo), known as '''[[Fortress Stadium (disambiguation)|Fortress]]''' ({{lang-sr|\u0422\u0432\u0440\u0452\u0430\u0432\u0430}} / Tvr\u0111ava), is a [[Soccer-specific stadium|football stadium]] in [[Smederevo]], [[Serbia]]. It is currently used mostly for [[Association football|football]] matches and is the home ground of [[FK Smederevo 1924]]. The stadium has a [[seating capacity]] for 17,200 spectators. The stadium was previously known as '''Sartid Stadium''' ({{lang-sr|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0424\u041a \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0434}} / Stadion FK Sartid).\n\n==History==\nThe stadium got its current appearance from its most recent reconstruction in 2000. The venue hosted a [[2009 European Cup]] [[rugby league]] match, when [[Serbia national rugby league team|Serbia]] played [[Wales national rugby league team|Wales]].\n\nIn late August 2012, an unidentified virus infected the grass at the stadium and forced [[FK Smederevo]] to play its fixtures outside of the stadium until the grass was changed.<ref>[http://www.sportske.net/vest/domaci-fudbal/nepoznata-bolest-napala-travu-na-stadionu-smedereva-93323.html Nepoznata bolest napala travu na stadionu Smedereva!?] ''www.sportske.net'' {{in lang|sr}}</ref>\n\n==International matches==\n[[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia national football team|FR Yugoslavia national football team]] played here once.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=\"30\" |#\n!width=\"150\"|Date\n!width=\"200\"|Competition\n!width=\"200\" |Opponent\n!width=\"100\"|Score\n!width=\"60\"|Att.\n!width=\"30\" |Ref\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\"|{{flag_icon|FR Yugoslavia}} '''[[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FR Yugoslavia]]''' (1992\u20132003)\n|-\n|1.||17 April 2002 ||align=\"left\"|[[Friendly match]] ||align=\"left\"|{{fb|LIT}} ||bgcolor=\"#00FF00\"|'''4\u20131 (2\u20131)''' ||15,000 ||<ref>[http://www.reprezentacija.rs/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=140&Itemid=60 SR Jugoslavija - Litvanija] ''www.reprezentacija.rs'' {{in lang|sr}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of football stadiums in Serbia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Football venues in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Multi-purpose stadiums in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Rugby league stadiums in Serbia]]\n[[Category:FK Smederevo]]\n\n\n{{Serbia-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Serbianboy87", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smederevo_Stadium"}
{"title_page": "1988 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1988\n| team= Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = WKU Hilltoppers wordmark.png\n| image_size= 175\n| conference= Independent\n| division= \n| short_conf= \n| STATSRank = \n| FCSCoachRank = 13\n| record = 9\u20134\n| conf_record = \n| head_coach= [[Dave Roberts (American football)|Dave Roberts]]\n| hc_year =5th\n| off_coach= \n| oc_year = \n| def_coach= \n| dc_year = \n| off_scheme= \n| def_scheme=\n| stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| champion = \n| bowl = [[1988 NCAA Division I-AA football season|Division I-AA Playoffs]]\n| bowl_result = Lost Quarterfinals\n}}\n{{1988 NCAA Division I-AA independents football standings}}\nThe '''1988 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky University]] in the [[1988 NCAA Division I-AA football season]] and were led by head coach [[Dave Roberts (American football)|Dave Roberts]]. The team earned their second consecutive NCAA Division 1-AA Playoff berth, making it to the quarterfinals.  The Hilltoppers finished the season ranked 13th in the final national poll.<ref>{{cite news|title=Final NCAA Division I-AA|newspaper=Daily Press|location=Newport News, Virginia|date=November 21, 1988|page=C4|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11011645/poll_1988_1121_iaa_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 4, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref>\nWestern Kentucky's roster included future [[National Football League|NFL]] players Tony Brown, Eddie Godfrey, Anthony Green, Jerome Martin, Xavier Jordan, Dean Tiebout, Jonathan Watts, and [[Riley Ware]].  Joe Arnold, Tiebout, and Dewayne Penn were named to the AP All American team.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1988\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 10\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 17\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1988|team=Morehead State Eagles|title=Morehead State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Jayne Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Morehead, KY]]\n| score = 34\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 17\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| rank = 17\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1988|team=Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders|title=Middle Tennessee}}\n| opprank = 15\n| site_stadium = [[Johnny \"Red\" Floyd Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Murfreesboro, TN]]\n| score = 10\u201313\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 24\n| w/l = w\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]\n| opprank = 8\n| gamename = [[Battle of the Bluegrass]]\n| site_stadium = [[L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Bowling Green, KY]]\n| score = 16\u201314\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 1\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 14\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1988|team=Austin Peay Governors|title=Austin Peay}}\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 28\u20133\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 8\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 10\n| opponent = [[Illinois State Redbirds|Illinois State]]\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 31\u201316\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 15\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 8\n| opponent = [[Missouri State Bears football|Southwest Missouri]]\n| site_stadium = [[Robert W. Plaster Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Springfield, MO]]\n| score = 21\u201314\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 22\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[Tennessee Tech Golden Eagles football|Tennessee Tech]]\n| site_stadium = [[Tucker Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Cookeville, TN]]\n| score = 20\u201317\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 29\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 5\n| homecoming = y\n| opponent = 